36 A BILL
37 TO BE ENTITLED
38 AN ACT
39
40 Relating to the Public Service Commission; to amend
41 Sections 37-1-3, 37-1-5, 37-1-6, and 37-1-7, Code of Alabama
42 1975; to provide for appointment of commissioners to the
43 Public Service Commission; to further provide for
44 qualifications of commissioners; to extend conflict of
45 interest provisions imposed on commissioners to include
46 actions with certain nonutility entities participating in
47 matters before the commission; to require the commission to
48 hold certain periodic public informational meetings with
49 utility representatives; to add Section 37-1-54.1 to the Code
50 of Alabama 1975, to require the commission to ensure lobbying
51 expenses are not charged to ratepayers; to amend Sections
52 17-14-1, 17-14-2, and 17-14-3, and 36-3-1, Code of Alabama
53 1975, to make conforming changes; and to make nonsubstantive,
54 technical revisions to update the existing code language to
55 current style.
56 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
Page 2

BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
HB392 INTRODUCED
57 Section 1. The Legislature hereby finds all of the
58 following:
59 (1) Alabama's current model for regulating critical
60 infrastructure and public service industries was established
61 over 100 years ago and is not the best model for ensuring that
62 Alabamians are best-served and well-positioned for future
63 challenges.
64 (2) Most states in America do not elect their state
65 regulatory bodies. Currently 40 states appoint their version
66 of the public service commission.
67 (3) There are dozens of regulatory bodies and agencies
68 in Alabama and none of them are elected. These include offices
69 regulating complex and critical industries including banking,
70 insurance, and many others.
71 (4) All current members of the public service
72 commission were initially appointed to their position by the
73 Governor.
74 (5) The law currently establishes no conflict of
75 interest restrictions on for profit and nonprofit advocacy
76 organizations' relationships with members of the commission
77 other than those entities that meet the definition of
78 "utility" under current law.
